Problems¶

Problem 1¶

Find the currents going through R2 and R4 in the following circuit

Solution

Mesh equations: $$ \begin{array}{l} \left(2 I_{1}+2 I_{3}\right)+\left(8 I_{1}+8 I_{2}\right)=40 \\ \left(8 I_{2}+8 I_{1}\right)+\left(6 I_{2}\right)+\left(6 I_{2}-6 I_{3}\right)=0 \\ \left(2 I_{3}+2 I_{1}\right)+\left(6 I_{3}-6 I_{2}\right)+\left(2 I_{3}\right)+\left(3 I_{3}\right)=20 \end{array} $$ Hence, $$ \begin{array}{l} 10 I_{1}+8 I_{2}+2 I_{3}=40 \\ 8 I_{1}+20 I_{2}-6 I_{3}=0 \\ 2 I_{1}-6 I_{2}+13 I_{3}=20 \end{array} $$ which leads to, $$ I_{1}=6,34 \mathrm{A}, I_{2}=-2,75 \mathrm{A}, I_{3}=-0,71 \mathrm{A} $$ Finally $$ I_{R2}=I_{1}+I_{3}=5,63 \mathrm{A}\\ I_{R4}=I_{3}-I_{2}=2,04 \mathrm{A} $$

Problem 2¶

Find the current going through R4 in the following circuit

Solution

Mesh equations $$ \begin{array}{l} \left(1 I_{1}\right)+\left(2 I_{1}+2 I_{2}\right)=20 \\ \left(2 I_{2}+2 I_{1}\right)+\left(1 I_{2}\right)+\left(1 I_{2}-1 I_{3}\right)=0\\ I_3=2mA \end{array} $$ Then,

$$ \begin{array}{l} 3 I_{1}+2 I_{2}=20 \\ 2 I_{1}+4 I_{2}-I_{3}=0 \\ I_{3}=2 \end{array} $$

The solution to the system of equations is, $$ I_{1}=9,5 \mathrm{mA}, I_{2}=-4,25 \mathrm{mA}, I_{3}=2 \mathrm{mA} $$ Then $$I_{R4}=I_3-I_2=6,25\mathrm{mA}$$

A=np.matrix('3,2,0;2,4,-1;0,0,1')
b=np.matrix('20;0;2')
x=solve(A,b)
print(x)

Problem 3¶

Find the current and voltage drop in through R4 in the following circuit. How many nodes are there?

Solution

Let's apply mesh analysis for the three lower meshes and the outer loop, assuming they are all clockwise. The equations are:

$$ \begin{array}{l} I_1(40+15)+I_2(-15)=15 \\ I_2=0.1\\ I_2(-10)+I_3(20)+I_4(10)=0 \\ I_2(4)+I_3(10)+I_4(20+10+4)=15 \\ \end{array} $$
In [3]:
A=np.matrix('55,-15,0,0;0,1,0,0;0,-10,20,10;0,4,10,34')
b=np.matrix('15;0.1;0;15')
x=solve(A,b)
print(x)

[[ 0.3       ]
 [ 0.1       ]
 [-0.19310345]
 [ 0.4862069 ]]

$I_{R4}=I_3+I_4=0.29A$

$\Delta V_{R4}=I_{R4}R_4=0.29\times10=2.9V$

Alternative solution: Let's combine R3 and R4 as they are in parallel, so $R_{eq}=(R_3R_4)/(R_3+R_4)=100/20=5\Omega$. It is not required, but we simplify the analysis as we now require 3 equations instead of 4. Now there are only 3 meshes.Using the outer loop instead of mesh 3

$$ \begin{array}{l} I_1(40+15)+I_2(-15)+I_3(0)=15 \\ I_2=0.1\\ I_2(5+4)+I_3(20+5+4)=15 \end{array} $$
In [13]:
A=np.matrix('55,-15,-40;0,1,0;0,9,29')
b=np.matrix('15;0.1;15')
x=solve(A,b)
print(x)

[[0.65360502]
 [0.1       ]
 [0.4862069 ]]

The net current is going though $R_4$ is then $I_{R_4}=(I_2+I_3)R_{eq}/R_4=0.29A$, which is the same as our previous result.

Problem 4¶

Find the Thevenin's equivalent between A and B

Solution

To calculate $V_{th}$, let us choose the the two lower meshes and the outer loop, then $$ \begin{array}{l} 55 I_{1}-15 I_{2}=17,4 \\ I_{2}=0,1 \\ 14 I_{2}+40 I_{3}=17,4 \end{array} $$ Then $$ I_{1}=0.34 \mathrm{~A} ; I_{2}=0.1 \mathrm{~A} ; I_{3}=0.4 \mathrm{~A} $$ Hence $$ V_{th}=10 \Omega \cdot (0.4+0.1) \mathrm{A}=5V $$ Now $R_{th}$:

There is a short circuit for the $40\Omega$ and $15\Omega$ resistors, so they do not contribute. Everything comes down to two resistors in parallel with values $10\Omega$ and $(25+4)\Omega$ $$ R_{th}=\frac{10 \Omega \cdot (26+4) \Omega}{10 \Omega+(26+4) \Omega}=7,5\Omega $$

In [26]:
A=np.matrix('55,-15,0;0,1,0;0,14,40')
b=np.matrix('17.4;0.1;17.4')
x=solve(A,b)
print(x)

 [0.1       ]
 [0.4       ]]
